50|$|Lophius vomerinus, {{commonly}} known as <b>devil</b> <b>anglerfish</b> or cape monk, is a species of anglerfish in the Lophiidae family. It was described by Achille Valenciennes in 1837. The species is known from Durban, South Africa as well as northern Namibia where it is found in Indian and Atlantic Oceans on the depths of 150 - 400 m. Sightings of it have also been recorded on Cape of Good Hope. The common length is 50 cm but can {{be as big as}} a 100 cm. It is similar to L. piscatorius but has different morphology.|$|E
50|$|Kr√∏yer's {{deep sea}} angler fish (Ceratias holboelli) is {{a species of}} fish in the family Ceratiidae, the sea <b>devils.</b> This deep-sea <b>anglerfish</b> is found in all oceans, at depths of 0 to 4400 m, but mainly between 400 and 2000 m. Females {{typically}} are 77 cm long, but can reach 120 cm. The much smaller males only reach 16 cm and they are symbiotic, as they attach themselves to a female.|$|R

